BIOFIELD SCIENCE - The true foundation to human health & energy healing practices 

If you’re ready to learn what has been hidden from the modern lexicon comment “BIOFIELD” to sign up for the Biofield Mastery Training Program today. 

In the late 1800s and early 1900s, electrotherapy was not fringe science.

It was taught in major medical schools, published in peer-reviewed journals, and practiced in hospitals across Europe and the United States. Electricity, vibration, and frequency were considered fundamental forces of life.

John Ernst Worrell Keely proposed that matter and biology were governed by harmonic vibration. He described disease as a state of disharmony, and health as restored resonance. 

His work influenced early ideas of sympathetic vibration, acoustics, and frequency-based healing, concepts that would later resurface in physics and biology under different names.

Georges Lakhovsky expanded this framework. His Multi-Wave Oscillator (MWO) was installed in hospitals and clinics throughout the U.S. and Europe. Lakhovsky showed that cells behave as oscillators and that illness reflects disrupted cellular frequencies. 

After his death in the early 1940s, MWOs were systematically removed from hospitals and his work quietly abandoned.

Royal Raymond Rife went further, developing optical microscopes capable of visualizing live microorganisms and frequency devices that reportedly destroyed pathogens without harming surrounding tissue. 

His clinical successes were documented, then challenged. Lawsuits, professional pressure, and regulatory shifts ended his practice.

The turning point came with the Flexner Report, which restructured medical education. Treatments that could not be patented, electricity, vibration, frequency, were removed from curricula. 

Pharmaceutical chemistry replaced energetic medicine.

What was once mainstream medical science was rebranded as quackery.

History didn’t disprove electromedicine.

It erased it.
